Economic Freedom Fighters(EFF) leader Julius Malema is on Monday morning appearing in the Newcastle Magistrate Court in KwaZulu-Natal over remarks he made in which he allegedly called for party supporters to take part in land invasions.Last month two summons were served on Malema by the National Prosecuting Authority. Malema is charged with contravening the Riotous Assemblies Act &amp; Trespass Act on two separate occasions namely 26 June 2014 and 16 Dec 2014.The National Prosecuting Authority(NPA) accuses Malema of instructing members of the EFF to occupy any vacant land wherever it may be found.CIC @Julius_S_Malema has arrived in court, with other EFF officials #HandsOffCIC pic.twitter.com/F7POdFdKpk EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) November 7, 2016Addressing supporters in Newcastle during celebrations commemorating the 61st anniversary of the Freedom Charter, Malema said: &#8220;If you see a piece of land, don t apologise, if you like it, go and occupy that land. That land belongs to us. The community of New Castle is present to defend CIC @Julius_S_MalemaLand Occupation is an assertion of th Freedom Charter! #HandsOffCIC pic.twitter.com/QfNcP6mXyV EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) November 7, 2016 The EFF has called on its members to come out and show support for their leader. Demonstrations have begun outside the court on Monday morning with members pledging their support for the party&#8217;s leader.Malema is also scheduled to appear in the Bloemfontein court on 14 November to face similar charges.&nbsp;TNA Reporter